<div class="body" id="fhbody-175712561">
	
		
	

	
		
		<div id="text-175712561" class="p">
			
		 	
				U.S. retailers are <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2024/12/online-returns-hassle-fees-fraud/681084/">cracking down on free returns</a> as costs spiral out of control, The Atlantic reports. Return rates have more than doubled since 2019, with shoppers expected to send back nearly $900 billion in merchandise this year.<br> <br>

Major chains like REI and JCPenney are now charging fees or requiring in-store drop-offs, abandoning years of customer-friendly policies. With each $100 return costing stores up to $30 to process, some retailers have given up entirely -- telling customers to keep cheap items rather than send them back.<br>
		 	
		</div>

		

		

		
			
		
	</div>
